## Investigation 2 — Brute Force Attack 🔵

### What is a Brute Force Attack?

A Brute Force attack systematically tries many username and password combinations against a login page until valid credentials are found. It is identified by a high volume of POST requests to a login endpoint from a single IP in a short time window.

**Log File:**
```
/root/Desktop/QuestionFiles/Brute-Forcing/access.log
```

---

### Step 1 — Check Status Code Distribution

```bash
cat /root/Desktop/QuestionFiles/Brute-Forcing/access.log \
  | awk '{print $9}' | sort | uniq -c
```

**Output:**
```
204 200
187 302
 15 404
```

> The attack showed as **302 redirects** (failed login redirecting back to login page) rather than the expected 401 Unauthorized — a common pattern in web apps with redirect-based authentication.

---

### Step 2 — Identify Attacker User Agent

```bash
cat /root/Desktop/QuestionFiles/Brute-Forcing/access.log \
  | awk -F'"' '{print $6}' | sort | uniq -c | sort -rn
```

**Output:**
```
372  Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) Chrome/112.0.5615.50  ← ATTACKER
 34  Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_15_7) Chrome/112.0.0.0
```

**Attacker's user agent:**
```
Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/112.0.5615.50 Safari/537.36
```

> ⚠️ The attacker spoofed a real Chrome browser user agent to blend in. Volume (372 requests) revealed the attacker — not the user agent name.

---

### Step 3 — Identify Attacker IP

```bash
grep "POST" /root/Desktop/QuestionFiles/Brute-Forcing/access.log \
  | awk '{print $1}' | sort | uniq -c | sort -rn
```

**Output:**
```
161  146.241.73.240  ← ATTACKER
```

> 161 POST requests to `/login` from a single IP in minutes — unmistakable fingerprint of an automated brute force tool.

---

### Step 4 — Find the Successful Login

```bash
grep "146.241.73.240" /root/Desktop/QuestionFiles/Brute-Forcing/access.log \
  | grep "POST.*login"
```

Every failed attempt returned the same response — status `200` body size `947` (the error page):
```
146.241.73.240 [26/Apr/2023:21:42:36] POST /login → 200 (size: 947) FAILED
146.241.73.240 [26/Apr/2023:21:42:37] POST /login → 200 (size: 947) FAILED
146.241.73.240 [26/Apr/2023:21:42:38] POST /login → 200 (size: 947) FAILED
... (repeated 161 times)

146.241.73.240 [26/Apr/2023:21:44:03] POST /login → 200 (size: 947) ← LAST ATTEMPT

146.241.73.240 [26/Apr/2023:21:44:23] GET /post?postId=1 → 200 ✅ LOGIN CONFIRMED
146.241.73.240 [26/Apr/2023:21:44:23] GET /post?postId=2 → 200 ✅
146.241.73.240 [26/Apr/2023:21:44:24] GET /post?postId=3 → 200 ✅
```

> The attacker stopped POST requests and immediately started browsing the site — the pivot from POST to GET confirmed a successful login.

---

### Summary — Brute Force

| Finding | Value |
|---------|-------|
| Attacker IP | `146.241.73.240` |
| User Agent | `Chrome/112.0.5615.50 (spoofed)` |
| Attack Endpoint | `POST /login` |
| Total Attempts | 161 POST requests |
| Failed Login Sign | Status 200, body size 947 |
| Successful Login | `26/Apr/2023 21:44:03` |
| Post-login Activity | Browsed all posts (1–10) immediately |
| Outcome | ✅ Attack successful — access gained |

