## Tools & Commands Used

| Tool | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `cat` | View full log file |
| `grep -E` | Filter lines using regex |
| `awk '{print $1}'` | Extract IP address field |
| `awk -F'"' '{print $6}'` | Extract user agent field |
| `awk '{print $9}'` | Extract status code field |
| `sort` | Sort results |
| `uniq -c` | Count unique occurrences |
| `sort -rn` | Sort by count, highest first |

---

## Key Lessons Learned

1. **Always check status codes first** — brute force appeared as 302, not the expected 401.
2. **Volume reveals the attacker** — 161 POST requests from one IP is always suspicious.
3. **Encoding evades filters** — URL encoding (`%2f`, `%5c`, `%09`) was used to bypass redirect validation.
4. **Behaviour change confirms success** — the POST to GET pivot confirmed the successful login without needing to see the password.
5. **Regex saves hours** — one grep command filtered hundreds of lines instantly.

